<title>BELGIUM: EU discusses export refund/animal welfare link.</title>
<headline>EU discusses export refund/animal welfare link.</headline>
<dateline>BRUSSELS 1997-07-23</dateline>
<text>
<p>EU farm ministers discussed technical problems with a proposal to make payment of export refunds for farm animals dependent on respect for animal welfare rules, Luxembourg Farm Minister Fernand said on Wednesday.</p>
<p>&quot;There's concern about public opinion following distressing scenes on television of animals being mistreated,&quot; Boden said after a meeting of EU farm ministers.</p>
<p>Among the problems were effective monitoring of the welfare of animals after they had left the EU.</p>
<p>Seven countries, including Germany, Sweden and Britain, want speedy action to improve animal welfare.</p>
<p>But some exporting countries, such as France and Ireland, are cautious about the cost of stricter animal welfare rules.</p>
<p>A decision cannot be taken until after the European Parliament has given its opinion in October.</p>
<p>The EU exports about 600,000 cattle, sheep and goats annually -- mostly to Egypt, Libya, Lebanon and Turkey. But EU livestock exports are mostly in the form of meat.</p>
